<section>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>The <code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code> component replaces native HTML <code>&lt;map&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;area&gt;</code> with percentage-based coordinates that scale responsively. Areas are defined as <code>&lt;map-area&gt;</code> children with rich HTML tooltip content, full keyboard navigation, and progressive enhancement.</p>

  <browser-window
    src="/docs/snippets/demos/image-map-basic.html"
    url="https://vanilla-breeze.dev/image-map"
    title="Image Map Demo"
    style="min-height: 38rem;"
    shadow>
  </browser-window>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Basic image map">{{ basicCode | escape }}</code-block>

  <aside class="note">
    <strong>Progressive enhancement:</strong> Without JavaScript, the image renders normally and each <code>&lt;map-area&gt;</code> displays as a labeled list item below. The overlay and tooltips only activate when JS registers the components.
  </aside>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Markup Pattern</h2>
  <p>Place an <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> as a direct child of <code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code>. The component adopts it and overlays an SVG hit-testing layer. Each <code>&lt;map-area&gt;</code> defines a hotspot region &mdash; its inner HTML becomes the tooltip content.</p>
  <p>Alternatively, <code>src</code> and <code>alt</code> attributes on <code>&lt;image-map&gt;</code> itself can create the image, but placing <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> as a child gives better progressive enhancement.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Coordinate System</h2>
  <p>All coordinates are <strong>percentages (0&ndash;100)</strong> of the rendered image dimensions &mdash; not pixels. Values are unitless numbers separated by spaces or commas. The SVG overlay uses <code>viewBox=&quot;0 0 100 100&quot;</code> so percentage coordinates map directly to SVG units with no runtime conversion.</p>

  <code-block language="html" show-lines label="All shape types">{{ shapesCode | escape }}</code-block>

  <table class="props-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Shape</th><th>Coords format</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>rect</code></td>
        <td><code>x1 y1 x2 y2</code></td>
        <td>Top-left and bottom-right corners</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>circle</code></td>
        <td><code>cx cy r</code></td>
        <td>Centre point and radius (radius is % of image width)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>poly</code></td>
        <td><code>x1 y1 x2 y2 ...</code></td>
        <td>Series of points (minimum 3), auto-closes</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

